aa(lp45
VIn rats, we can ask this question and answer it.
p46
aVSo what we did is a cross-fostering experiment.
p47
aVYou essentially separate the litter, the babies of this rat, at birth,
p48
aVto two kinds of fostering mothers \u2014
p49
aVnot the real mothers, but mothers that will take care of them:
p50
aVhigh-licking mothers and low-licking mothers.
p51
aVAnd you can do the opposite with the low-licking pups.
p52
aVAnd the remarkable answer was,
p53
aVit wasn't important what gene you got from your mother.
p54
aVIt was not the biological mother that defined this property of these rats.
p55
aVIt is the mother that took care of the pups.
p56
aVSo how can this work?
p57
aa(lp58
VI am an a epigeneticist.
p59
aVI am interested in how genes are marked
p60
aVby a chemical mark
p61
aVduring embryogenesis, during the time we're in the womb of our mothers,
p62
aVand decide which gene will be expressed
p63
aVin what tissue.
p64
aVDifferent genes are expressed in the brain than in the liver and the eye.
p65
aVAnd we thought: Is it possible
p66
aVthat the mother is somehow reprogramming the gene of her offspring
p67
aVthrough her behavior?
p68
aVAnd we spent 10 years,
p69
aVand we found that there is a cascade of biochemical events
p70
aVby which the licking and grooming of the mother, the care of the mother,
p71
aVis translated to biochemical signals
p72
aVthat go into the nucleus and into the DNA
p73
aVand program it differently.
p74
aVSo now the animal can prepare itself for life:
p75
aVIs life going to be harsh?
p76
aVIs there going to be a lot of food?
p77
aVAre there going to be a lot of cats and snakes around,
p78
aVor will I live in an upper-class neighborhood
p79
aVwhere all I have to do is behave well and proper,
p80
aVand that will gain me social acceptance?
p81
aVAnd now one can think about how important that process can be
p82
aVfor our lives.
p83
aa(lp84
VWe inherit our DNA from our ancestors.
p85
aVThe DNA is old.
p86
aVIt evolved during evolution.
p87
aVBut it doesn't tell us if you are going to be born in Stockholm,
p88
aVwhere the days are long in the summer and short in the winter,
p89
aVor in Ecuador,
p90
aVwhere there's an equal number of hours for day and night all year round.
p91
aVAnd that has such an enormous [effect] on our physiology.
p92
aVSo what we suggest is, perhaps what happens early in life,
p93
aVthose signals that come through the mother,
p94
aVtell the child what kind of social world you're going to be living in.
p95
aVIt will be harsh, and you'd better be anxious and be stressful,
p96
aVor it's going to be an easy world, and you have to be different.
p97
aVIs it going to be a world with a lot of light or little light?
p98
aVIs it going to be a world with a lot of food or little food?
p99
aVIf there's no food around,
p100
aVyou'd better develop your brain to binge whenever you see a meal,
p101
aVor store every piece of food that you have as fat.
p102
aa(lp103
VSo this is good.
p104
aVEvolution has selected this
p105
aVto allow our fixed, old DNA to function in a dynamic way
p106
aVin new environments.
p107
aVBut sometimes things can go wrong;
p108
aVfor example, if you're born to a poor family
p109
aVand the signals are, "You better binge,
p110
aVyou better eat every piece of food you're going to encounter."
p111
aVBut now we humans and our brain have evolved,
p112
aVhave changed evolution even faster.
p113
aVNow you can buy McDonald's for one dollar.
p114
aVAnd therefore, the preparation that we had by our mothers
p115
aVis turning out to be maladaptive.
p116
aVThe same preparation that was supposed to protect us from hunger and famine
p117
aVis going to cause obesity,
p118
aVcardiovascular problems and metabolic disease.
p119
aVSo this concept that genes could be marked by our experience,
p120
aVand especially the early life experience,
p121
aVcan provide us a unifying explanation
p122
aVof both health and disease.
p123
aa(lp124
VBut is true only for rats?
p125
aVThe problem is, we cannot test this in humans,
p126
aVbecause ethically, we cannot administer child adversity in a random way.
p127
aVSo if a poor child develops a certain property,
p128
aVwe don't know whether this is caused by poverty
p129
aVor whether poor people have bad genes.
p130
aVSo geneticists will try to tell you that poor people are poor
p131
aVbecause their genes make them poor.
p132
aVEpigeneticists will tell you
p133
aVpoor people are in a bad environment or an impoverished environment
p134
aVthat creates that phenotype, that property.
