aa(lp136
VSo we moved to look into our cousins, the monkeys.
p137
aVMy colleague, Stephen Suomi, has been rearing monkeys
p138
aVin two different ways:
p139
aVrandomly separated the monkey from the mother
p140
aVand reared her with a nurse
p141
aVand surrogate motherhood conditions.
p142
aVSo these monkeys didn't have a mother; they had a nurse.
p143
aVAnd other monkeys were reared with their normal, natural mothers.
p144
aVAnd when they were old, they were completely different animals.
p145
aVThe monkeys that had a mother did not care about alcohol,
p146
aVthey were not sexually aggressive.
p147
aVThe monkeys that didn't have a mother were aggressive, were stressed
p148
aVand were alcoholics.
p149
aVSo we looked at their DNA early after birth, to see:
p150
aVIs it possible that the mother is marking?
p151
aVIs there a signature of the mother in the DNA of the offspring?
p152
aa(lp153
VThese are Day-14 monkeys,
p154
aVand what you see here is the modern way by which we study epigenetics.
p155
aVWe can now map those chemical marks, which we call methylation marks,
p156
aVon DNA at a single nucleotide resolution.
p157
aVWe can map the entire genome.
p158
aVWe can now compare the monkey that had a mother or not.
p159
aVAnd here's a visual presentation of this.
p160
aVWhat you see is the genes that got more methylated are red.
p161
aVThe genes that got less methylated are green.
p162
aVYou can see many genes are changing,
p163
aVbecause not having a mother is not just one thing \u2014
p164
aVit affects the whole way;
p165
aVit sends signals about the whole way your world is going to look
p166
aVwhen you become an adult.
p167
aVAnd you can see the two groups of monkeys
p168
aVextremely well-separated from each other.
p169
aVHow early does this develop?
p170
aVThese monkeys already didn't see their mothers,
p171
aVso they had a social experience.
p172
aVDo we sense our social status, even at the moment of birth?
