aa(lp174
VSo in this experiment, we took placentas of monkeys
p175
aVthat had different social status.
p176
aVWhat's interesting about social rank is that across all living beings,
p177
aVthey will structure themselves by hierarchy.
p178
aVMonkey number one is the boss;
p179
aVmonkey number four is the peon.
p180
aVYou put four monkeys in a cage,
p181
aVthere will always be a boss and always be a peon.
p182
aVAnd what's interesting is that the monkey number one
p183
aVis much healthier than monkey number four.
p184
aVAnd if you put them in a cage,
p185
aVmonkey number one will not eat as much.
p186
aVMonkey number four will eat [a lot].
p187
aVAnd what you see here in this methylation mapping,
p188
aVa dramatic separation at birth
p189
aVof the animals that had a high social status
p190
aVversus the animals that did not have a high status.
p191
aa(lp192
VSo we are born already knowing the social information,
p193
aVand that social information is not bad or good,
p194
aVit just prepares us for life,
p195
aVbecause we have to program our biology differently
p196
aVif we are in the high or the low social status.
