aa(lp198
VBut how can you study this in humans?
p199
aVWe can't do experiments, we can't administer adversity to humans.
p200
aVBut God does experiments with humans,
p201
aVand it's called natural disasters.
p202
aa(lp203
VOne of the hardest natural disasters in Canadian history
p204
aVhappened in my province of Quebec.
p205
aVIt's the ice storm of 1998.
p206
aVWe lost our entire electrical grid because of an ice storm
p207
aVwhen the temperatures were, in the dead of winter in Quebec,
p208
aVminus 20 to minus 30.
p209
aVAnd there were pregnant mothers during that time.
p210
aVAnd my colleague Suzanne King followed the children of these mothers
p211
aVfor 15 years.
p212
aa(lp213
VAnd what happened was, that as the stress increased \u2014
p214
aVand here we had objective measures of stress:
p215
aVHow long were you without power? Where did you spend your time?
p216
aVWas it in your mother-in-law's apartment or in some posh country home?
p217
aVSo all of these added up to a social stress scale,
p218
aVand you can ask the question:
p219
aVHow did the children look?
p220
aVAnd it appears that as stress increases,
p221
aVthe children develop more autism,
p222
aVthey develop more metabolic diseases
p223
aVand they develop more autoimmune diseases.
p224
aVWe would map the methylation state,
p225
aVand again, you see the green genes becoming red as stress increases,
p226
aVthe red genes becoming green as stress increases,
p227
aVan entire rearrangement of the genome in response to stress.
